  "prompt": "Which badminton shuttlecock is better: Mavis 350 or Mavis 500?",
  "response": "When comparing the **Mavis 350** and **Mavis 500** shuttlecocks, the decision largely depends on your playing style, skill level, and specific needs. Both are nylon (plastic) shuttlecocks from **Yonex**, but they have distinct characteristics:\n\n### **Mavis 350**\n- **Speed**: Medium\n- **Durability**: More durable than feather shuttlecocks, but less than the Mavis 500.\n- **Flight**: Offers a good balance of speed and control.\n- **Audience**: Ideal for intermediate players or those looking for a reliable shuttlecock for casual play or training.\n- **Cost**: More affordable than the Mavis 500.\n\n### **Mavis 500**\n- **Speed**: Faster than the Mavis 350.\n- **Durability**: Extremely durable, designed for long-lasting use.\n- **Flight**: Provides a more consistent and faster flight, closer to the performance of feather shuttlecocks.\n- **Audience**: Better suited for advanced players or those who want a shuttlecock that mimics the feel of feather shuttles during practice or competitive play.\n- **Cost**: Slightly more expensive than the Mavis 350.\n\n### **Which is Better?**\n- If you\u2019re a beginner or intermediate player and prioritize durability and cost, the **Mavis 350** is a solid choice.\n- If you\u2019re an advanced player or want a shuttlecock that offers better performance and speed, the **Mavis 500** is worth the investment.\n\nUltimately, your choice should align with your skill level, playing frequency, and budget. If possible, try both to see which one feels better for your game!",
